# Broch with-postgres-external + Caddy production configuration
#
#   cp .env.example .env
#   # edit .env
#   docker compose up -d --build


# ── Required ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Broch master key — the at-rest encryption root. Required; the server won't
# start without it. Generate a strong random value: `openssl rand -base64 48`.
BROCH_MASTER_KEY=

BROCH_WILDCARD_HOSTNAME=broch.example.com

# Caddy DNS-01 + Let's Encrypt. These credentials let Caddy prove you own the domain (by
# writing a TXT record) so it can issue your wildcard TLS cert — they are for CERT ISSUANCE
# ONLY, never user sign-in (login is the AUTHENTICATION__* values further down). Set the
# credential(s) for ONE provider — the one your tls.caddy `dns ...` block references; leave
# the rest empty. (All provider modules are compiled into the broch-caddy image; the active
# provider is chosen in tls.caddy.)
CADDY_ACME_EMAIL=
# Cloudflare (default tls.caddy):
CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN=
# Azure DNS — credentials Caddy uses to solve the ACME DNS-01 challenge (writing a TXT
# record in your zone to prove ownership and get the wildcard cert). These are for cert
# issuance only, NOT user sign-in — your IdP/login credentials are the AUTHENTICATION__*
# values further down. AZURE_DNS_RESOURCE_GROUP is the resource group holding the DNS zone.
# Managed identity (subscription + resource group only, no secret):
# AZURE_DNS_SUBSCRIPTION_ID=
# AZURE_DNS_RESOURCE_GROUP=
# Service principal (add these to the above — for an app registration instead of a managed identity):
# AZURE_DNS_TENANT_ID=
# AZURE_DNS_CLIENT_ID=
# AZURE_DNS_CLIENT_SECRET=
# AWS Route 53 — standard AWS SDK env names (kept verbatim so the SDK recognizes them);
# an IAM principal with list+change rights on the hosted zone. Route 53 DNS only:
# AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=
# AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=
# Google Cloud DNS — GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS is the standard Google ADC env var (a
# path to a service-account JSON, with roles/dns.admin, mounted into the caddy container);
# the SDK reads it by that exact name. GCP_PROJECT is the project hosting the DNS zone:
# GCP_PROJECT=
# GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS=/etc/caddy/certs/gcp-sa.json
# DigitalOcean — personal access token with write scope on DNS:
# DO_AUTH_TOKEN=

# Connection string for your external Postgres. Format expected by Npgsql:
#
#   Host=<host>;Port=5432;Database=<db>;Username=<user>;Password=<pass>;SSL Mode=Require
#
# Examples:
#
#   DigitalOcean Managed:
#     Host=broch-db-do-user-1234.b.db.ondigitalocean.com;Port=25060;Database=brochdb;Username=broch;Password=YOUR-DB-PASSWORD;SSL Mode=Require
#
#   AWS RDS:
#     Host=broch.abc123.us-east-1.rds.amazonaws.com;Port=5432;Database=brochdb;Username=broch;Password=YOUR-DB-PASSWORD;SSL Mode=Require
#
#   Neon / Supabase (or any Postgres-as-a-service with TLS):
#     Host=ep-cool-name-12345.us-east-1.aws.neon.tech;Database=brochdb;Username=broch;Password=YOUR-DB-PASSWORD;SSL Mode=Require
#
# SSL Mode values: Require (default for managed services), Prefer, Disable.
BROCH_DB_CONNECTION_STRING=


# ── Identity provider (required at boot) ─────────────────────────────────────
#
# Broch authenticates every user through your IdP — there is no built-in local
# login, so the IdP is part of the boot floor. The server starts without these,
# but no one can sign in (or finish first-run setup) until they're set. Your
# first admin is whoever signs in holding a role named in ADMINROLES.
# Setup guides: https://broch.io/docs/identity-providers/

# Provider: Auth0 | AzureAd | EntraExternalId | Okta | Oidc
# (No inline comments after values — dotenv passes them through as part of
# the value and the server rejects it at boot.)
AUTHENTICATION__PROVIDER=
AUTHENTICATION__CLIENTID=
AUTHENTICATION__CLIENTSECRET=
# broch_admin is an example — replace with admin group(s)/role(s) from your
# own IdP that your first admin actually holds. Comma-separated; holding any
# listed role grants admin.
AUTHENTICATION__ADMINROLES=broch_admin

# Set the value(s) your provider needs; leave the rest blank:
#   Auth0 / Okta:     AUTHENTICATION__DOMAIN=your-tenant.auth0.com
#   AzureAd / Entra:  AUTHENTICATION__TENANTID + AUTHENTICATION__INSTANCE=https://login.microsoftonline.com/
#   Oidc (generic):   AUTHENTICATION__AUTHORITY=https://issuer.example.com
#   Auth0 RBAC:       AUTHENTICATION__AUDIENCE=<your-api-identifier>  (only if roles arrive via the access token)
AUTHENTICATION__DOMAIN=
AUTHENTICATION__TENANTID=
AUTHENTICATION__INSTANCE=
AUTHENTICATION__AUTHORITY=
AUTHENTICATION__AUDIENCE=


# ── Optional ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Broch license is activated in-app on first sign-in (Admin → License) — there's
# no env var for it. Buy a license at https://broch.io/pricing.

# Broch server image tag. Defaults to a concrete pinned version (see docker-compose.yml).
# Override to upgrade deliberately, or set BROCH_VERSION=latest to float (not recommended).
# BROCH_VERSION=1.31.0
# Image repo defaults to the public ghcr.io/broch-io/broch. Override only for a private mirror
# or a pre-release/beta image you've been granted (then `docker login` to that registry first):
# BROCH_IMAGE=ghcr.io/broch-io/broch

# Trusted-proxy CIDRs broch accepts X-Forwarded-For/-Proto from (comma-separated). The compose
# default (172.16.0.0/12) covers Docker's default address pool, i.e. the network Caddy reaches
# broch on. Override only if your Docker daemon uses custom address pools, or if an external
# load balancer fronts this host. Seeded on first boot; Admin → Share Settings wins afterwards.
# BROCH_TRUSTED_PROXY_CIDRS=172.16.0.0/12
